Raneem Sayyad

27 April 2025

Research Question

This study explores geographic differences in synthetic opioid use across the United States in 2022, with a focus on fentanyl and related substances such as Acetyl fentanyl, Fluorobutyryl fentanyl, and Fluorofentanyl. The research investigates behavior (synthetic opioid drug reports), space (U.S. states), and time (calendar year 2022). Key variables include the number of drug reports per synthetic opioid by state, measured using data from the 2022 NFLIS dataset. Data analysis using Multidimensional Scaling (MDS) and pattern grouping with K-means clustering was used to help visualize and understand differences across states.

Research Question:

Did synthetic opioid use, specifically fentanyl, vary significantly across U.S. states in 2022?

Literature Review

In a study by Angelini et al.(2020), the authors investigated the use of lateral flow immunoassays (LFIs) to quickly detect fentanyl in seized drug samples and postmortem urine. The main question was whether two different LFI configurations (dipsticks and cassettes) could effectively identify fentanyl in real world samples. They tested 44 drug samples and 14 urine samples, using gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS) as a confirmation method. The results showed that both LFI types detected fentanyl with no false negatives. The dipstick LFIs had 100% sensitivity, 75% specificity, and 93.2% efficiency, while the cassettes had 100% sensitivity, specificity, and efficiency for drug samples. These findings suggest LFIs could be a quick and cost-effective tool for fentanyl detection in forensic and law enforcement applications.

Citation:

Angelini, D. J., Biggs, T. D., Prugh, A. M., Smith, J. A., Hanburger, J. A., Llano, B., Avelar, R., Ellis, A., Lusk, B., Malik Naanaa, A., Sisco, E., & Sekowski, J. W. (2021). The use of lateral flow immunoassays for the detection of fentanyl in seized drug samples and postmortem urine. Journal of Forensic Sciences, 66(2), 758765. https://doi.org/10.1111/1556-4029.14631

Data

I used the 2022 NFLIS (National Forensic Laboratory Information System) public drug data from the DEA, which is the most recent and updated release. The data includes toxicology reports for 60 drug types across all U.S. states. After downloading and unzipping the file, I cleaned the data in Excel by deleting headers and footers, placing all states in a single row, and removing derivatives of drug subtype entries. I formatted all numbers as numbers by removing commas and prepared the file for import into R software. This dataset provides a complete overview of drugs seized in 2022 across the U.S., making it useful for national analysis. A key advantage is that it is publicly accessible and detailed by state and drug type. However, the main limitation is that it only covers one year, making it difficult to study trends over time, and the data only shows seized drugs analyzed by laboratories. This process and data can be easily replicated by downloading the 2022 NFLIS dataset from the DEAs official site and following the same Excel cleaning steps.

Methods

I imported the NFLIS 2022 data into R and loaded the necessary libraries, including cluster, ggpubr, ggrepel, and tidyverse. I then transposed the data, using the four synthetic opioids Acetyl fentanyl, Fentanyl, Fluorobutyryl fentanyl, and Fluorofentanyl as columns to analyze state-level drug reports. I applied Multidimensional Scaling (MDS), a technique that helps simplify complex data into two dimensions, making it easier to see how states differ based on these drugs. To better understand the data, I used K-means clustering to group states with similar drug patterns. The results were shown in a scatter plot, with each state color-coded by cluster, and labeled using ggrepel for clear distinction. This approach helped visualize how different states are related in terms of synthetic opioid use. To further analyze the NFLIS 2022 data, I performed a second round of Multidimensional Scaling (MDS), but this time with states as the dimensions. I adjusted the data so that each states drug reports were in columns, with drug names as rows. MDS was used to reduce the data into two dimensions, helping to visualize differences in synthetic opioid use across states. I then applied K-means clustering with three clusters to group states with similar drug patterns. The plot displayed states in MDS space, color-coded by their cluster, with labels added using ggrepel to show the drugs. The final visualization highlighted how states clustered based on synthetic opioid use.

Findings

Finding 1

Analysis of the 2022 fentanyl related report data reveals that Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Arizona formed a distinct cluster characterized by markedly high synthetic opioid activity as seen in Visual 1. Ohio reported 17,910 fentanyl cases, Arizona reported 16,975, and Pennsylvania followed with 13,355. These numbers were significantly higher than those of most other states, clearly positioning this cluster as an outlier compared to the other states. Even when considering analog substances like fluorofentanyl, Arizona and Pennsylvania reported notable counts of 298 and 3,051. These findings, derived from clustering the states based on report volumes, show that synthetic opioid use was not evenly distributed across the U.S. in 2022. Instead, use was heavily concentrated in specific areas, particularly in these three states, demonstrating significant variation across regions.

Finding 2

A second distinct cluster includes New Jersey, Florida, Virginia, New York, and California, each displaying moderate levels of synthetic opioid reports in 2022, as seen in Visual 1. This cluster displayed high levels of fentanyl reports, but not to the extreme seen in the first cluster. California reported 10,872 fentanyl cases, New York had 9,188, Florida recorded 7,442, New Jersey had 9,225, and Virginia reported 7,545. Although these states had thousands of fentanyl cases, the numbers were consistently lower than those of Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Arizona. Reports of fluorofentanyl were also present, though again at lower levels, with California reporting 699 cases and New York reporting 513. This cluster highlights that while synthetic opioid use was widespread, the intensity varied by location. This analysis further confirms that synthetic opioid use in 2022 varied significantly across states, by showing a clear difference in scale between different clusters of states.

Finding 3

In examining Visual 2, methamphetamine use appears isolated and distinct from other substances. Methamphetamine displayed a separate trajectory, with use patterns that were not strongly tied to states with high synthetic opioid activity. In analyzing the data subset table created for the MDS and K-means clustering plot, the isolation was evident through high numbers of methamphetamine reports in several states. This includes California (48,297 reports), Arizona (7,667 reports), Oklahoma (10,860 reports), and Missouri (15,676 reports). These elevated numbers suggest that methamphetamine was a dominant substance in certain states, following a different pattern compared to other drugs. Methamphetamine follows a regional pattern, particularly concentrated in the Southwest and Western regions of the United States. The isolated positioning of methamphetamine in the MDS Visual 2 plot indicates that its distribution across U.S. states was substantially different in 2022. Confidence in this finding is high due to the consistency between the data table and the clustering visual. However, the data may not fully capture recent events, and reporting inconsistencies between states could impact the overall accuracy. Still, the strong separation observed in both the numerical data and visual analysis supports the conclusion that synthetic opioid use exhibited strong patterns across states in 2022.

Finding 4

By examining Visual 2, a cluster including cocaine, fentanyl, and cannabis/THC was grouped closely together. This shows a similar pattern of use across states in the U.S. in 2022. The cluster highlights that states with higher fentanyl reports also tended to report high cocaine and cannabis cases. This is distinct because it implies that states with high fentanyl use are also likely experiencing higher use of cocaine and cannabis. For example, states such as Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Arizona, which led in fentanyl cases, also showed strong cocaine and cannabis reporting. Therefore, synthetic opioid use, specifically fentanyl, varied significantly across states, but often alongside variation in other substances like cocaine and cannabis. A limitation in using this dataset remains, as the dataset does not separate cause from correlation. For example, whether fentanyl is being mixed into other opioids or whether users are switching between drugs. The data appears to be complete but misses key information on co-use patterns that could lead to incomplete understandings.

Finding 5

In examining the data table presented in Visual 3, it is clear that while fentanyl was widely reported across the United States in 2022, the presence of fentanyl analogs such as acetyl fentanyl, fluorobutyryl fentanyl, and fluorofentanyl was much more limited. For example, Alabama reported 325 fentanyl cases but only 2 cases of acetyl fentanyl and 51 cases of fluorofentanyl. A similar pattern can be seen in Illinois, which had 5,281 fentanyl reports but just 30 reports for acetyl fentanyl and 360 for fluorofentanyl. Even in states where fentanyl reports were extremely high, such as Ohio with 17,910 cases and Arizona with 16,975 cases, the number of analog reports remained relatively low. Ohio had 880 acetyl fentanyl cases and 5,259 fluorofentanyl cases, while Arizona reported only 39 acetyl fentanyl cases and 298 fluorofentanyl cases. This consistent pattern across the data shows that although analogs were present, they were far less common than fentanyl itself. Fentanyl clearly remained the dominant synthetic opioid reported in most states during 2022. This suggests that synthetic opioid use not only varied in volume from state to state but also varied in the type of substances reported. Most states were primarily dealing with fentanyl rather than a mix of analogs. This finding suggests that synthetic opioid use specifically pertaining to fentanyl did indeed differ significantly across the United States in 2022.

So What

This study is very important for criminal justice professionals, public health agencies, and government officials. Especially in the context of the growing fentanyl epidemic that continues to threaten national security, community safety, and public health. By focusing on particular clusters of high and moderate synthetic opioid activity, these findings can guide the strategic allocation of resources in a more data-driven way. This study is important for a variety of organizations, not just law enforcement, in tackling the fentanyl crisis. By pinpointing regions with high and moderate synthetic opioid activity, particularly in states like Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Arizona, it provides a roadmap for more focused action. This could mean prioritizing law enforcement efforts, expanding harm-reduction programs, or increasing access to naloxone. Public health agencies can use this data to target addiction treatment and prevention efforts, while emergency medical services can better prepare for fentanyl related overdoses. Local governments and nonprofit groups can also direct resources where theyre most needed. Forensic labs and border control can use this information to improve the detection of new drug trends and better respond to threats. Ultimately, this approach moves away from broad, one-size-fits-all strategies and focuses on state specific solutions that make the best use of limited resources. Moving forward, future research could focus on the import and export patterns of fentanyl, using this data as a reference to better understand how synthetic opioids are entering the country. By analyzing supply chains and tracking the distribution routes, researchers can pinpoint key points of entry, uncover trends in trafficking, and identify international networks involved in the trade. Additionally, research could help make policy changes and improve coordination between domestic and international authorities to combat the distribution of fentanyl more efficiently.
